1) @TrackTime is a custom annotation which prints logs for method execution time.
I have a OrderService in Spring boot application.
Which has printServiceName() which is private and applies @TrackTime. Will this works?

RC:
The short answer is no, the @TrackTime annotation will not work on a private method in a standard Spring Boot application.
Spring handles annotations under the hood using the Proxy Pattern.

Why it fails: The Proxy Pattern
Spring doesn't actually add code to your classes.
Instead, it creates a Proxy (a wrapper) around your bean.
When another component calls a method on your OrderService, it is actually calling a method on the Proxy.
The Proxy starts the timer, calls your real method, and then stops the timer.


The "Visibility" Problem
-----------------------
CGLIB Proxies:
-------------
By default, Spring Boot uses CGLIB to create proxies by subclassing your OrderService.
Since private methods are not visible to subclasses, the proxy cannot "override" or wrap them.

Internal Calls:
Even if the method were protected, if you call printServiceName() from another method inside the same class (e.g., createOrder() calls printServiceName()),
the call stays inside the "real" object and never hits the Proxy.
This is known as Self-Invocation.
***Note: We have already faced this issue while calling @Transactional on methodA() methodB() from same class. methodA() call methodB(0 directly, it wont call through APO proxy.

Fixes:
 1) Change visibility of method from private to public
 2) Move the logic to helper class.
 3) Switch from Spring AOP to AspectJ
 *** AspectJ uses "Compile-time" or "Load-time" weaving, which modifies the actual bytecode of your class rather than using a Proxy.
 This is more powerful but significantly more complex to configure.
 4) Manual Execution (The "Quick & Dirty"): Not recommended

 private void printServiceName() {
     StopWatch sw = new StopWatch();
     sw.start();
     // ... logic ...
     sw.stop();
     log.info("Execution time: {} ms", sw.getTotalTimeMillis());
 }








